Sure, here's a simple code example in Java to illustrate how abstraction enables the creation of modular, easy-to-maintain code:

```
public interface Animal {
   public void makeSound();
}

public class Dog implements Animal {
   public void makeSound() {
       System.out.println("Woof!");
   }
}

public class Cat implements Animal {
   public void makeSound() {
       System.out.println("Meow!");
   }
}

public class Main {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
       Animal dog = new Dog();
       Animal cat = new Cat();
       dog.makeSound();
       cat.makeSound();
   }
}
```

In this example, we have an Animal interface that defines a makeSound() method. We also have two classes, Dog and Cat, that implement this interface and provide their own implementation of the makeSound() method.

In the main() method, we create objects of type Dog and Cat and store them in variables of type Animal. This allows us to use polymorphism to call the makeSound() method on each object, even though they are of different types.

By using abstraction through the Animal interface, we can create a set of classes that share a common set of properties and behaviors. This allows us to create modular, reusable code that is easy to maintain over time.

Sure, here's another example that shows how abstraction can help create modular and easy-to-maintain software:

```
public interface Shape {
    public double calculateArea();
}

public class Circle implements Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    public double calculateArea() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}

public class Rectangle implements Shape {
    private double length;
    private double width;

    public Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    public double calculateArea() {
        return length * width;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape circle = new Circle(5);
        Shape rectangle = new Rectangle(3, 4);

        System.out.println("Area of circle: " + circle.calculateArea());
        System.out.println("Area of rectangle: " + rectangle.calculateArea());
    }
}
```

In this example, we create an abstract Shape interface that defines a method called calculateArea(). We then create two concrete classes, Circle and Rectangle, which implement the Shape interface and provide their own implementation of the calculateArea() method.

The benefit of using abstraction in this case is that we can use the Shape interface to create a set of generic functions that can work with objects of any shape that implements the Shape interface. Instead of writing separate functions for each type of shape, we can write a single function that takes in an object of type Shape, and then use the calculateArea() method to calculate the area of the shape.

This approach creates modular and easy-to-maintain code, since we can add new shapes to our program simply by implementing the Shape interface and providing an implementation for the calculateArea() method. Additionally, if we need to make changes to the way that area is calculated for a particular shape, we can simply update the relevant class and the changes will propagate throughout our codebase.

