```python
import numpy as np
from abc import ABCMeta, abstractmethod

class RegressionModel(metaclass=ABCMeta):

    @abstractmethod
    def fit(self, X, y):
        pass

    @abstractmethod
    def predict(self, X):
        pass

class LinearRegression(RegressionModel):

    def __init__(self):
        self.coefficients = None

    def fit(self, X, y):
        X = np.c_[np.ones(X.shape[0]), X]
        self.coefficients = np.linalg.inv(X.T.dot(X)).dot(X.T.dot(y))

    def predict(self, X):
        X = np.c_[np.ones(X.shape[0]), X]
        return X.dot(self.coefficients)

class PolynomialRegression(RegressionModel):

    def __init__(self, degree):
        self.degree = degree
        self.coefficients = None

    def fit(self, X, y):
        X_poly = np.zeros((X.shape[0], self.degree + 1))
        for i in range(self.degree + 1):
            X_poly[:,i] = X.ravel() ** i
        self.coefficients = np.linalg.inv(X_poly.T.dot(X_poly)).dot(X_poly.T.dot(y))

    def predict(self, X):
        X_poly = np.zeros((X.shape[0], self.degree + 1))
        for i in range(self.degree + 1):
            X_poly[:,i] = X.ravel() ** i
        return X_poly.dot(self.coefficients)
```

The above code implements a RegressionModel class as an abstract base class to create linear regression and polynomial regression models as subclasses. The RegressionModel class forms the abstraction, as it defines the essential methods required for any type of regression model.

The LinearRegression class is created as a subclass of RegressionModel and inherits the fit() and predict() methods from the base class. It also encapsulates the regression model-specific details such as storing the coefficients and adding an intercept term to the input.

The PolynomialRegression class is created as a subclass of RegressionModel, but requires a degree parameter to specify the order of the polynomial. It overrides the fit() and predict() methods to include the polynomial-specific regression calculations such as transforming the input data to a polynomial matrix and storing the coefficients.

This implementation demonstrates the power of object-oriented programming in encapsulating complex models and creating reusable code. With this structure, we can easily switch between various types of regression models based on the input data and requirements without modifying the core implementation of RegressionModel. Additionally, this code is easily extendable to introduce new types of regression models by simply creating a new subclass of RegressionModel and implementing the required methods.
